rican Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Quincy","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): habitational name from any of several places in France deriving their names from the Gallo-Roman personal name <i>Quintus</i>, meaning ‘fifth(-born)’ + the locative suffix <i>-acum</i>. The earliest bearer of the name in England, that of Saer de <i>Quincy</i>, ancestor of the earls of Winchester, was from Cuinchy in Pas-de-Calais, but the name may have been reinforced by immigrants from Quincy-sous-Sénard in Seine-et-Oise or Quincy-Voisins in Seine-et-Marne. A family of the name <i>de Quincy</i> held the title Earl of Winchester 1207–65. Descendants of this family later bore the name <i>Quincey</i> up to the time of the English essayist Thomas <i>De Quincey</i> (1785–1859), who changed his name from <i>Quincey</i> to <i>De Quincey</i> in 1796.","History: The American Quincy family were established in MA by Edmund Quincy in 1633. Fifth in descent was Josiah Quincy (1744–75), a leading patriot, who was sent to England to argue the colonists’ case in 1774. His son Josiah (1772–1864) was a powerful opponent of slavery, president of Harvard, and mayor of Boston, a post also held by several of his descendants. The traditional pronunciation is “Quinzy”."],"variants":[{"name":"Quincey","meanings":["English: variant of   Quincy  ."]}]},{"name":"Saher","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Early morning, dawn’."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705184,"age":6,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705185,"age":16,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Lord Saher de Quincy was born in 1090, in Daventry, Northamptonshire, England, his father, Richard de Quincy, was 24 and his mother, Judith Orabilis, was 18. He married Matilda de Senlis about 1136. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. He died about 1158, in Winchester, Hampshire, England, at the age of 69, and was buried in Winchester, Hampshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1090–about 1158":"1090–umbes 1158","1090–1158":"1090–1158","1092–Female":"1092–Surnud","1090–1163":"1090–1163","1138–1190":"1138–1190","1140–1197":"1140–1197","1140–1204":"1140–1204","1066–1098":"1066–1098","1073–Female":"1073–Surnud","1190":"1190","1090":"1090","about 1140":"umbes 1140","1066":"1066","1098":"1098","1197":"1197","1163":"1163","1096":"1096","1140":"1140","1073":"1073","1092":"1092","1106":"1106","1138":"1138","1204":"1204","1158":"1158","about 1136":"umbes 1136","about 1158":"umbes 1158","Leicestershire, England":"Leicestershire, England","Winchester, Hampshire, England":"Winchester, Hampshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Scotla